{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657255"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.6,0.27,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82614"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11873"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5312"},{"type":"tags","id":"11114"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28240"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82614"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA copper intrauterine device can be left in position for periods of 5 \u2013 10 years and used as a method of ongoing contraception.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is their most common side effect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Device expulsion","Dysmenorrhoea","Heavy menstrual bleeding","Intermenstrual spotting","Uterine perforation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe copper intrauterine device (IUD) is a highly effective, long-acting, reversible contraceptive that provides non-hormonal contraception for up to 10 years. Understanding its side effects is crucial for appropriate patient counselling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy menstrual bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common side effect of copper IUDs, affecting up to 50% of users. The copper ions cause a local inflammatory reaction in the endometrium, which can lead to increased menstrual flow and duration. This effect is most pronounced in the first three to six months after insertion but may persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysmenorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E is a common side effect, affecting approximately 30% of users. Like heavy menstrual bleeding, it tends to be most severe in the first few months after insertion and may improve with time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermenstrual spotting\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in about 20% of users, particularly in the first three months after insertion. This typically resolves spontaneously as the body adjusts to the device.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevice expulsion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in approximately 2-10% of users, most commonly in the first year of use. Risk factors include nulliparity, heavy menstrual bleeding, and immediate post-partum insertion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine perforation\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication occurring in approximately 1-2 per 1000 insertions. The risk is higher during insertion in lactating women due to uterine involution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heavy menstrual bleeding is the most common side effect of copper intrauterine devices, affecting up to 50% of users","Copper intrauterine devices are a highly effective, long-acting, non-hormonal contraceptive option","Most side effects of copper intrauterine devices occur in the first three months after insertion"],"references":["Hubacher et al. Side effects from the copper IUD: do they decrease over time? Contraception. 2009. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2702765/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19139"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T11:52:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T11:54:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11873"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82614"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms